			\textbf{3. \LaTeX-Syntax} \bigskip
			
			In \LaTeX{} special commands are used for typesetting a text or document. 
			These commands are usually a combination of special characters and letters, do not allow for any spaces and are case sensitive
				\footnote{
					\tiny Case sensitive means that upper- and lowercase are treated as distinct. For example, \textit{command1} and \textit{Command1}  	
					\tiny would be two different commands and not interchangeable. Case sensitivity is also a common source of error, as commands    
					\tiny must be entered as intended (e.g. \textbackslash\textit{LaTeX\{\}}  vs. \textit{\st{\textbackslash latex\{\}}}).
					}			
			. Similarly to the valency of a verb in language, \LaTeX{} commands can be classified by the number of arguments they take. 
			In general, they can be categorised into two major groups: \bigskip{}
			
			1.) Zero-Argument-Commands 
			
			2.) Non-Zero-Argument-Commands \bigskip{}
									
			%------------------------- %
			% Basic Commands %
			%------------------------- %			
			
			\textbf{3.1 Zero-Argument-Commands} \bigskip{}
			
			\foreignlanguage{english}{\enquote{Zero-Argument-Commands}} are commands that do not require any additional arguments - at least 
			on the surface level - and that can be used intransitively (i.e. on their own). 
			These commands generally consist of three components: 
			1.) a backslash, 2.) a simple word or phrase indicating the function of the command and 3.) (empty) curly brackets. 
			They can be notated as:
		
		\end{flushleft}

			\colorbox{yellow}{\textit{\textbackslash somecommand\{\}}} \bigskip

		\begingroup
			\fontsize{9pt}{11pt}\selectfont

				Ex. 1) \bigskip

				\textit{\textbackslash LaTeX\{\}} \hspace{10mm} – \hspace{5mm} displays the \foreignlanguage{english}{\enquote{LaTeX}} symbol (\LaTeX)

				\textit{\textbackslash noindent\{\}} \hspace{6.6mm} – \hspace{5mm} suppresses paragraph indentation

				\textit{\textbackslash bigskip\{\}} \hspace{9mm} – \hspace{5mm} creates a vertical empty space

		\endgroup		

		\begin{flushleft}

			Since basic commands like this do not take on any specified arguments, the curly brackets (for more detail see 3.2) may be left out. 
			While this normally does not entail any loss of function, it can lead to minor behavioural differences (such as inserting or deleting a space), 
			especially when the command is a direct part of the text: 

		\end{flushleft}
			
		\begingroup
			\fontsize{9pt}{11pt}\selectfont
			
				\textit{\textbackslash LaTeX is cool}  \hspace{10mm} vs. \hspace{10mm} \textit{\textbackslash LaTeX\{\} is cool}

			\begingroup
				\fontsize{7.5pt}{10pt}\selectfont			
		
					\hspace{1mm} (= \LaTeX is cool) \hspace{30mm} (= \LaTeX{} is cool)
			
			\endgroup

		\endgroup		

